result.execSummary:
The defendant Domonick M Williams was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Endanger Safety/Reckless Use of Firearm, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(2)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Domonick M Williams in court with attorney John Mathew Krejci.  Randall L Schneider appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing hearing held.  Statements made as to sentencing.  

AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS (CONSECUTIVE TO ANY OTHER SENTENCE), with credit for 3 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  The defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is eligible for the "Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program".

Court orders restitution set at $0. 
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.
Court ordered defendant to pay all applicable court costs and surcharges.
As to all costs and surcharges, Court orders amounts to be deducted from bail on deposit.  As to remaining amount (if applicable), Court orders DOC shall collect up to 25% of prison funds.  Balance to be paid during the period of extended supervision.  Unpaid portion to convert to a civil judgment.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

Defendant changes plea to GUILTY as to amended charge in COUNT 1, Endangering Safety by Use of a Dangerous Weapon.  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court orders ATTEMPT MODIFIER AND PARTY TO A CRIME MODIFIER DISMISSED (AS TO COUNT 1) AND COUNT 2 DISMISSED and READ-IN.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Plea questionnaire, addendum, and jury instruction received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the amended information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms or body armor.  Defendant is advised he unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for June 9, 2016 at 08:30 am.
